This is by no means a solitary instance of the existence of studs of practically wild mares, who with their young, until such age as they could be made available for work,were allowed to roam at will in the open pasturage. Siniilar cases are met with, to name but one instance, in the Rievaulx Chartulary. Thus (f. 67¹³) Bernard de Baliol makes grant—“ Communam pasturam lx matribus equabus eum nutrimento suo per totam forestam meam de Thesedale, ita ut pulli et pultrae earum, cum aetatem ii annorum habuerint, inde removebuntur.’' The eharter, a little further on, proceeds thus: “ Concedo etiam eis omnia asiamenta in praedicta foresta mea; scil. materiam ad faldas faciendas ad equas illaqueandas, et logias ad opus pastorum, . . . et ut in praedicta pastura animalium—scil. infra Egleshope 01 Stodeshope faciant logias ad opus pastorum animalium, et faldas ad opus animalium ; 01 ut libertatem habeant per totam terram meam eundi et redeundi, et ducendi animalia sua ad pasturam, et reducendi.⁷’ And without dwelling upon the possible significance of the name “ Stodes- hope,’' it is plain from this extract, even had it not been abundantly apparent on the surface, that the work of catching the wild mares and their progeny must have been one involving some labour and preparation, both of such a nature as to require the services of not a few men.
